TY  - JOUR
T1  - Bond Yields and the Federal Reserve
AU  - Piazzesi, Monika
Y1  - 2005/04/01
PY  - 2005
DA  - 2005/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/427466
DO  - 10.1086/427466
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 311
EP  - 344
VL  - 113
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Bond yields respond to policy decisions by the Federal Reserve and vice versa. To learn about these responses, I model a high?frequency policy rule based on yield curve information and an arbitrage?free bond market. In continuous time, the Fed?s target is a pure jump process. Jump intensities depend on the state of the economy and the meeting calendar of the Federal Open Market Committee. The model has closed?form solutions for yields as functions of a few state variables. Introducing monetary policy helps to match the whole yield curve, because the target is an observable state variable that pins down its short end and introduces important seasonalities around FOMC meetings. The volatility of yields is ?snake shaped,? which the model explains with policy inertia. The policy rule crucially depends on the two?year yield and describes Fed policy better than Taylor rules.
AB  - Bond yields respond to policy decisions by the Federal Reserve and vice versa. To learn about these responses, I model a high?frequency policy rule based on yield curve information and an arbitrage?free bond market. In continuous time, the Fed?s target is a pure jump process. Jump intensities depend on the state of the economy and the meeting calendar of the Federal Open Market Committee. The model has closed?form solutions for yields as functions of a few state variables. Introducing monetary policy helps to match the whole yield curve, because the target is an observable state variable that pins down its short end and introduces important seasonalities around FOMC meetings. The volatility of yields is ?snake shaped,? which the model explains with policy inertia. The policy rule crucially depends on the two?year yield and describes Fed policy better than Taylor rules.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/427466
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/427466
Y2  - 2024/03/19
