TY  - JOUR
T1  - Urban Decline and Durable Housing
AU  - Glaeser, Edward L.
AU  - Gyourko, Joseph
Y1  - 2005/04/01
PY  - 2005
DA  - 2005/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/427465
DO  - 10.1086/427465
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 345
EP  - 375
VL  - 113
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Urban decline is not the mirror image of growth, and durable housing is the primary reason the nature of decline is so different. This paper presents a model of urban decline with durable housing and verifies these implications of the model: (1) city growth rates are skewed so that cities grow more quickly than they decline; (2) urban decline is highly persistent; (3) positive shocks increase population more than they increase housing prices; (4) negative shocks decrease housing prices more than they decrease population; (5) if housing prices are below construction costs, then the city declines; and (6) the combination of cheap housing and weak labor demand attracts individuals with low levels of human capital to declining cities.
AB  - Urban decline is not the mirror image of growth, and durable housing is the primary reason the nature of decline is so different. This paper presents a model of urban decline with durable housing and verifies these implications of the model: (1) city growth rates are skewed so that cities grow more quickly than they decline; (2) urban decline is highly persistent; (3) positive shocks increase population more than they increase housing prices; (4) negative shocks decrease housing prices more than they decrease population; (5) if housing prices are below construction costs, then the city declines; and (6) the combination of cheap housing and weak labor demand attracts individuals with low levels of human capital to declining cities.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/427465
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/427465
Y2  - 2024/03/19
